ce:section.ce:para:
During the formation of P, N-CDs, phosphoric acid condensed with hydroxyl groups and occupied the corresponding position to form abundant phosphate ester groups on the surface of P, N-CDs. Phosphate ester groups featured strong electron-withdrawing ability. The electron of hydroxyl oxygen was more inclined to biase to phosphate groups, which weakened the electron-donating ability of O atom and blocked the intramolecular charge transfer (ICT) process. ALP is an enzyme that can hydrolyze phosphate ester to produce phosphoric acid. When ALP was presented in the P, N-CDs-based sensing system, it triggered the enzymatic dephosphorylation process. As the consequence, the surficial phosphate moiety of P, N-CDs was specifically cleaved, and the liberated hydroxyl groups enhanced the electron contributing ability, thus, the ICT effect resumed and the fluorescence strongly turned on at 530 nm throughout the whole process [21,47]. Fig. S4 illustrated the surface charge analysis of P, N-CDs with/without the presence of ALP. The as-synthesized P, N-CDs is near electrically neutral with a zeta potential of + 0.358 mV, due to the existence of phosphorus groups and imine groups on the surface. The enzymatic process induced by ALP led to the dephosphorylation of P, N-CDs, which made the surface of P, N-CDs more positively charged (+20.9 mV) from + 0.358 mV. The dephosphorylation induced by ALP was further verified by FT-IR. Compared with the original P, N-CDs (
Fig. S5
), the peaks in the FI-IR spectrum of P, N-CDs after addition of ALP at 528 cm−1 and 854 cm−1 were reduced, indicating the decrease in the number of COP due to the cleavage of PO bond. At the same time, obvious enhancement on the bands at 960 cm−1 and 600 cm−1 were observed, corresponding to the stretching vibration and in-plane bending vibration of PO4 3-. Moreover, the characteristic peaks at 1600 cm−1 and 3350 cm−1 corresponding to the benzene ring and the hydroxyl of phenol increased clearly, contributed by the exposure of hydroxyl groups. Nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR 31P) analysis was conducted to confirm the ALP dephosphorylating process. As shown in Fig. S6 , P, N-CDs displayed a 31P signal at δ (ppm) −15.62, which shifted to δ (ppm) 7.28 after the presence of ALP, attributed to the produce of free PO4 3- via the enzymatic dephosphorylation procedure. The produced free PO4 3- were further verified via ammonium molybdophosphate (AMP) precipitation method, and yellow precipitate was clearly observed in P, N-CDs after the addition of ALP ( Fig. S7 ). These results well revealed that P, N-CDs was dephosphorylated efficiently by ALP.

Nanoparticles generally interact with cell membrane first and then enter the cells through endocytosis pathways including clathrin-mediated endocytosis, caveolin-mediated endocytosis, lipid raft-mediated endocytosis, macropinocytosis, clathrin-independent endocytosis and caveolin-independent endocytosis [29,48,49]. To probe the pathways involved in the internalization of P, N-CDs, HeLa cells were treated with biochemical inhibitors of energy-dependent processes, various-mediated endocytosis and macropinocytosis. 2-deoxyglucose (2-DG) was employed to inhibit the energy-dependent pathway. Amiloride (AMI) was an inhibitor of pinocytosis. Methyl-β-cyclodextrin (MβCD), chlorpromazine (CHP) and genistein (GEN) respectively blocked lipid raft-, clathrin- and caveolae-mediated endocytosis pathways. By calculating the OPD of internalized P, N-CDs, it turned out that there were fewer apparent fluctuations in internalization rate of P, N-CDs after cells were incubated with different inhibitors (
                           Fig. S10
                        ). None of the above specific chemical inhibitors showed obvious effects on the endocytosis for P, N-CDs, suggesting that the entry of P, N-CDs into cells might follow passive diffusion pathways, rather than endocytosis. To verify this conjecture, the fluorescence images of living cells and fixed cells at different incubation times were recorded. The fluorescence was enhanced in both cells over time, which further revealed that energy was not required for transmembrane transport of P, N-CDs. Due to the increased membrane permeability of fixed cells, the fluorescence intensity was about ∼ 2-fold higher than that of live cells at each time period (
                           Fig. S11
                        ). Therefore, we eventually considered that P, N-CDs got into cells through passive diffusion [29,50].
